title: For Sale:  War Clubs
postcontent:
Welcome, one and all. As you can see my name is Lee and I would like to speak with you today about War Clubs. Here in the mountains and foothills, as in most of the world, spring has blossomed and with it naturally follows the time of the new War Club. With the insolent encroachment of aggressive vegetation and the unwanted and unwarranted advances of the lovelorn who have awoken from their winter slumber, spring has traditionally been the time of clubbly armament and re-equipage. I doesnt matter if you are replaceing a club lost or damaged in last year's campaign or are flexing your fingers in anticipation of grasping your very first, I am the man you need to talk to.

At this time I currently have three clubs in hand and ready for immediate shipment. Let us consider them all together and then one by one.



To begin, I present Phlegmlor, the largest and longest of the three. With mighty Phlegmlor at you side you need fear nothing under the brutal Sun.



Phlegmlor's prodigious head is crafted of the finest hot rolled tool steel and boasts a full six, four edged protuberances with a solid pyramidal spike on top.. When it comes to edged protuberances, six is always the perfect number. 



Phlegmlors shaft is made of fine, figured black Walnut, and is hafted by a semi-dished butt to keep the hand planted. The wood is polished and oiled with a Tung oil finish to keep its beauty for generations of use. Phlegmlor is 27 and 1/2 inches from tail to tip.

Now, we move onwards with the dark horse and pocket battleship of todays collection. Allow me to intrduce Lymphgar! 



Lymphgar knows no equal for lumpy spikes and sports seven pyramids of thump in two, stacked, offset rows of three with one more topping the crown.



Lymphgar is made of the same fine steel and polished Walnut only having a considerable knob on the end of the shaft to aid the grip. Lymphgar stretches a full 23 inches.



Lastly, and with whispered glee, I offer the last of the three. Cindy. 



Cindy has no warm wooden center and is solid steel through and through. Like the rocky shores of Antarctica Cindy is all cold, hard, icy business with a slightly tapered end to keep you holding on in adverse conditions. Cindy is not to be trifled with!



Cindy is 20 inches long of brushed steel with a tiny hard center of chromalloy.



And again with all three including a standard beer bottle for size reference.




You have a hard descision to make. Any of the three would make a fine companion in this springs reawakening. But which will it be? Mighty Phlegmlor? Immoveable Lymphgar. Svelte and icy Cindy? Only you can decide.



 As an aside, and I feel somewhat discomfited even making mention, but we all know that among us are those who although otherwise perfectly charming may have a slight problem with understanding the norms and moreys under which we in this society are burdened. Also, those who are less than adept at decoding interpersonal communication and/or non verbal gestures and signals. It is to those that I respectfully address the following. If you happen to cross paths in the public thouroughfare with any member species of the Constabulary while carrying any one of these fine instruments and it is NOT Halloween night or you are not with similarly dressed and arrayed persons obvioulsy on your merry way to a costume party or fancy dress ball you will be assured of some excitement. I don't mean excitement in front of you, or around you. The excitement will be most assuredly happening TO you. Although, you, yourself, will probably also be excited to some degree. Do not let this happen. It is usually better for the individual to happen to other people, and not to let them happen to you.

Ah yes, this sordid business of price. $130 each shipped to the cont US. 100 local pick up. Otherwise, further arrangements will have to be made. These are all handmade works of Clubby art made by myself with quality and longevity in mind. I can also make many other similar or dissimilar things on request. . Thanks for looking and I hope spring slides up into summer for you with the greatest of ease and satisfaction.

Lee at 479871764four

title: For Trade:  '67 Gibson B45 12 string, for TRADE
postcontent: An authentic Gibson 12 string from the Kalamazoo plant, from that classic Gibson period of the late 60's. Serial# puts it at 1967. Tobacco sunburst top, natural mahogany sides and back. This is the square shouldered model-- not the slope shouldered, and it has the trapeze bridge, which essentially eliminates the problem of "bellying" or bridge pulling that are so common with 12 strings. Nice bright, full sound that you'd expect from a Gibson. Action is nice and low, neck is solid and straight as an arrow, and saddle has plenty of room for adjustment. Completed items on ebay have these going for anywhere from $1500 to $2500. But the market is down here in NH, and not a lot of people have cash to throw around, so I'm checking to see what people might have to offer for trades. Often trades can benefit both parties more than a cash sale. Would make a nice gift for a collector or player.  This is NOT a "brand new" guitar-- it's got its share of nicks and dings and repairs. While it's been restored and has a clean bill of health, it's been played, and has lots of mojo; it's a players guitar, for sure.

title: For Sale:  Silencerco  Spectre II
postcontent:
It is not only super tough, but also one of the quietest .22 suppressors known to man. With the Spectre 22, users will also enjoy its multi-caliber versatility.

The Spectre 22 has a unique CTA baffle design for easy disassembly and is user serviceable, which is very important for any .22 lr silencer. Because the .22 lr round is not copper jacketed, molten lead and carbon debris will explode into the silencer when the projectile exits the muzzle. After some time it is possible for a .22 suppressor to fill completely with lead and become heavy and ineffective. To avoid this issue .22 silencers must be able to be disassembled for cleaning and regularly maintained. Most .22 silencers on the market can be disassembled for cleaning, however they require cleaning every 50 to 200 rounds or often times they will fuse together and they are unable to come apart. When the lead and carbon debris adhere to the inner wall of the silencer tube and fill the spaces between the baffles and the tube, there is simply too much build up of fouling and lead to remove the tube from most .22 lr silencers on the market. The Spectre 22 has the unique CTA baffle design that keeps the carbon and lead debris from reaching the silencer tube allowing it to be disassembled easily.

title: For Sale:  Silencerco  Sparrow
postcontent:
OVERVIEW

The Sparrow 22 is the first silencer in the world to offer the patented multi part containment (MPC) technology, which allows the Sparrow 22 to be easily disassembled for cleaning and maintenance after heavy use.

Because the .22 LR round is not copper jacketed, molten lead and carbon debris will explode into the silencer when the projectile exits the muzzle. After some time, it is possible for a .22 suppressor to fill completely with lead and become heavy and ineffective. To avoid this issue, .22 silencers must be disassembled for cleaning and regular maintenance.

Until Silencerco introduced the Sparrow 22, the only .22 silencers that could be disassembled for cleaning required a cleaning every 50 to 200 rounds. However, often the components of those silencers would be fused together and unable to come apart. Competitor products on the market have baffles in their .22 silencers that must be removed by twisting the outer tube around the baffles and/or sliding the outer tube off of the baffles. When the lead and carbon debris adhere to the inner wall of the outer tube and fill the spaces between the baffles and the outer tube, there is simply too much buildup of fouling and lead to remove the outer tube in that manner.

NOT FOR SALE WHERE PROHIBITED.

PAYMENT & FFL
Visa, Mastercard, money orders, cashier's checks will be gladly accepted. Visa & Mastercard sales will have a 3% fee added to the total. If you’re paying with a personal check, we must wait for the check to clear before we can ship the firearm, this can take between 10-14 days.

Please arrange to have your local FFL dealer fax or email us a signed current copy of their federal firearms license after the sale as all payments and paperwork must be received within 7 days of the end of auction. It is not our responsibility to contact them. If you cannot comply with that, then please do not bid.

Washington state residents will be charged 8% sales tax. This is not an option.

SHIPPING
Buyer pays the shipping cost listed in the auction (this includes insurance). Handguns are shipped using Registered Mail or Priority Mail depending on the amount of insurance required. Long guns are shipped via UPS Ground, FedEx, or Parcel Pro.

If you live in Washington State, then you can come and pick the item up to waive the shipping cost. All other areas, the buyer must arrange for the item to be shipped to a local FFL holder. Buyer must e-mail or fax a signed, current copy of the FFL holder's license before item may be shipped.

Due to shipping regulations, some restrictions may apply.

U.S. sales only.

LEGAL REQUIREMENTS
All firearms must be transferred through a licensed FFL dealer in your area. The bidder is required to supply a current, signed copy of their local dealer's license before shipment. It is the buyer's responsibility to find out if there are any special regulations in their area before bidding.

All firearms, including antique/black powder, require FFL paperwork and will be shipped to an FFL dealer. No exceptions!

Sorry, no sales California residents, New York, Massachusetts, New Jersey, Hawaii, Alaska, and Illinois.

All state and local laws apply, please be sure you can own the items you are bidding on.

SAFETY NOTICE
The buyer is solely responsible for determining that a used firearm is safe to shoot. The firearms offered have not been test fired. Whether purchased here or somewhere else we urge every buyer to have any used firearm they purchase inspected by a qualified gunsmith before firing.

RETURN POLICY
All firearms come with a 3-day (Monday through Friday) inspection/return privilege. The inspection period begins at the time of delivery to your dealer. It is the buyer's responsibility to inspect the firearm within this time frame. In case of a return, the buyer pays all shipping costs. This does not cover items damaged in shipment; you must save the damaged shipping box and file a claim with the appropriate shipping company. All returned items must be in the exact condition that they left us.

NOT FOR SALE WHERE PROHIBITED.

PAYMENT & FFL
Visa, Mastercard, money orders, cashier's checks will be gladly accepted. Visa & Mastercard sales will have a 3% fee added to the total. If you’re paying with a personal check, we must wait for the check to clear before we can ship the firearm, this can take between 10-14 days.

Please arrange to have your local FFL dealer fax or email us a signed current copy of their federal firearms license after the sale as all payments and paperwork must be received within 7 days of the end of auction. It is not our responsibility to contact them. If you cannot comply with that, then please do not bid.

Washington state residents will be charged 8% sales tax. This is not an option.

SHIPPING
Buyer pays the shipping cost listed in the auction (this includes insurance). Handguns are shipped using Registered Mail or Priority Mail depending on the amount of insurance required. Long guns are shipped via UPS Ground, FedEx, or Parcel Pro.

If you live in Washington State, then you can come and pick the item up to waive the shipping cost. All other areas, the buyer must arrange for the item to be shipped to a local FFL holder. Buyer must e-mail or fax a signed, current copy of the FFL holder's license before item may be shipped.

Due to shipping regulations, some restrictions may apply.

U.S. sales only.

LEGAL REQUIREMENTS
All firearms must be transferred through a licensed FFL dealer in your area. The bidder is required to supply a current, signed copy of their local dealer's license before shipment. It is the buyer's responsibility to find out if there are any special regulations in their area before bidding.

All firearms, including antique/black powder, require FFL paperwork and will be shipped to an FFL dealer. No exceptions!

Sorry, no sales California residents, New York, Massachusetts, New Jersey, Hawaii, Alaska, and Illinois.

All state and local laws apply, please be sure you can own the items you are bidding on.

SAFETY NOTICE
The buyer is solely responsible for determining that a used firearm is safe to shoot. The firearms offered have not been test fired. Whether purchased here or somewhere else we urge every buyer to have any used firearm they purchase inspected by a qualified gunsmith before firing.

RETURN POLICY
All firearms come with a 3-day (Monday through Friday) inspection/return privilege. The inspection period begins at the time of delivery to your dealer. It is the buyer's responsibility to inspect the firearm within this time frame. In case of a return, the buyer pays all shipping costs. This does not cover items damaged in shipment; you must save the damaged shipping box and file a claim with the appropriate shipping company. All returned items must be in the exact condition that they left us.

SAFETY NOTICE

RETURN POLICY
